title: For Sale:  JUST REDUCED FROM $950 Springfiel Model 1873 Trapdoor
postcontent:
THIS IS A PART OF AMERICAN HISTORY! OWN IT!
The Springfield Model 1873 was the first breech loaded rifle adopted by the U.S. Military. This infantry model in .45-70-Gov't Caliber was owned by my great grandfather who served the Union Army in the Signal Corps during the Civil war. 
The Springfield 1873 design was chosen for service from approximately 100 MFG's rifles submitted to the army. The single shot "Trap Door" design was chosen for its reliability even over faster repeating designs which tended to jam more readily. A recruit could load & shoot 8 rounds/ minute while an expert infantryman about 16/minute. 
The rifles were later used in the Spanish/American war and as buffalo rifles. 
This rifle is in good shape with minor nicks & scratches on the stock & forend. The U.S., U.S. Springfield, Eagle emblem, Serial Number (139949), & Model No. are clearly visible on the barrel, breech mechanisms, & butt plate.

Henry H001TV Lever-Action .17 HMR Rifle with 20″ Octagon Barrel, Walnut Stock, 10+1 Capacity

Like stagecoaches, swinging saloon doors and Pony Express riders, there are many innovations of the Old West that have long faded from use and live on only in Western movies and history books.

But there are still a few frontier staples that were so effective and ahead of their time that they remain in use today. Take, for instance, the intimidating octagonal barrels commonly found on the repeating rifles of that period. These heavy-duty workhorses sported added mass and extra weight to aid in heat absorption, making them the forerunners to the bull barrels used on modern target and varmint rifles.

So as a tip of our Stetson in honor of this timeless barrel style, we replaced the standard round barrel normally used on our world-famous rifles with a classic 20″ octagonal model, like those favored by the cowpunchers, lawmen, homesteaders and outlaws who blazed the trail westward across America. We rounded out this traditional look with an easy-to-adjust Marbles semi-buckhorn rear sight with a diamond insert and a highly visible brass beaded front sight seated in standard 3/8″ dovetail slots. A metal barrel band secures both the barrel and the high-capacity tubular magazine to the highgrade American walnut stock.

The popular Henry Lever action is now available in a frontier version with a 20″ octagonal barrel, fully adjustable semi buckhorn rear sight, beaded front sight and metal band. Features the famous smooth Henry action and American walnut stock. The receiver is already grooved to accomodate a scope.

title: For Sale/Trade:  BERETTA ITALIAN 92 FS A1 (New Model)  w/accessories
location: Laurel, south of Meridian, Meridian, Mississippi
postcontent:
2014 Beretta 92 FS A1, all original and as new. This gun is made in the Beretta Italy factory and is stamped as such on the slide.

 I special ordered an Italian model (took 6 weeks to get).  Tests I read of this FSA1 and M9A1 indicated the Italian made gun had tighter tolerances since it was not meant for combat. Also because I wanted the gun to be in that beautiful lustrous Beretta bluing. 

It does not disappoint in the looks department. It is a very good looking and good shooting gun. It does not have the same finish as the new 2014 M9 (American made model and also a fine gun). 

Very little use, less than 1 box of ammo. I fired two magazines through it (37 rounds). Dependable and accurate. I disassembled it (which is easy) cleaned it good and stored it. No scratches or marks at all, looks as new.

Also different from the M9, it has the 3-dot sights. 

The 92 FS A1 has added features over a standard FS Model. It has a rounded trigger guard, as opposed to the previous squared off model, which gives it a sleeker look, in my opinion. This is how the original Italian 92 looked. The rail on front is obvious. Less obvious is the enhanced internal frame rails.

 Also has the new front sight that can be changed without gunsmithing tools. Slides out and locks back tightly into place Description of all this is on Beretta’s web site.  

Comes with a new military web holster and military web pistol belt light brown (sand) colored, both never used in the field, only took out of the bag and placed the gun in it.  

Guns also comes with 3 new Beretta factory high capacity mags and a Beretta factory mag loader. Includes Beretta hard padded case, original box, factory bore brushes, Beretta factory gun lock and all original paperwork.  

I also have two full boxes of Federal factory ammo that goes with it. 

As
